–1365":"1302–1365","1321–1398":"1321–1398","1250–Male":"1250–Overleden","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1250":"1250","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1300":"1300","1321":"1321","1453":"1453","1398":"1398","1365":"1365","1320":"1320","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Wragby, Lincolnshire, England":"Wragby, Lincolnshire, England","Wragby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wragby, Lincolnshire, England","Forfarshire, Scotland":"Forfarshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1300–1360":"1300–1360","1300–1340":"1300–1340","1302–1365":"1302–1365","1321–1398":"1321–1398","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1250":"1250","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1300":"1300","1321":"1321","1453":"1453","1398":"1398","1365":"1365","1320":"1320","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Wragby, Lincolnshire, England":"Wragby, Lincolnshire, England","Wragby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wragby, Lincolnshire, England","Forfarshire, Scotland":"Forfarshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Swinstead","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Swinstead (Lincs).","2  English: locative name from various places named with the genitive singular of Old English  <i>swīn</i> ‘swine, pig’ +  <i>hēafod</i> ‘head’, primarily including Swineshead (Lincs, Beds), but perhaps also Swineyard Hall in Rostherne (Cheshire), recorded as  <i>Swinesheued</i> in 1184, and  <i>Swineserd</i> in Saint Martins without Worcester (Worcs)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":15,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":28,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":37,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William Swinstead II was born in 1300, in Wragby, Lincolnshire, England as the son of William Swinstead I. He married Alice Warhall in 1320, in Wragby, Lincolnshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1360, in his hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1300–1360":"1300–1360","1300–1340":"1300–1340","1302–1365":"1302–1365","1321–1398":"1321–1398","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1250":"1250","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1300":"1300","1321":"1321","1453":"1453","1398":"1398","1365":"1365","1320":"1320","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Wragby,